Motivation for Visible Points

Baake and Hucke say that Delone Sets and Meyer Sets, describing atomic arrangements, are already "well-understood". To me, these might be pre-requisisites for this paper, or at least these topics are mature enough and we can try to experiment with these ourselves.

def gcd(a,b):
    x,y = abs(a),abs(b)
    while(True):
        if (x > y):
            x,y = y,x
        elif (x == 0):
            return y
        else:
            y = y - x

Density of the Visible Points

Proposition

the visible points are uniformly discrete but not relatively dense. The natural density is $\frac{6}{\pi^2}$.

  • $V$ contains holes of arbitrary size that repeat lattice periodically
  • given inradius $\rho > 0$, there is sublattice of $\mathbb{Z}^2$ depending on $\rho$ with suitable translate being centers of holes with radius at least $\rho$
  • $GL(2,\mathbb{Z})$ acts transitively on $V$ and one has the partition $\displaystyle \mathbb{Z}^2 = \bigcup_{m \in \mathbb{N}} V$ of $\mathbb{Z}^2$ into $GL(2, \mathbb{Z})$ invariant sets.

Open Question: Communication of Patterns

How might the set of visible points be useful to an engineer or a computer scientist ? An auto mechanic or a girl scout selling cookies does not need to understand the set of visible points. It's not clear who benefits from understanding this set and why.

In a sense, the set of visible points diescribes anything we might call a pattern. I go to church twiwe a week on Friday and Sunday... we get the pattern oxxxxox and the fraction (2,7) or possibly (2,5) depennding on whether you compare x and o or to the entire interval.

Even the pattern "once a month" is rather rich in content. Do we mean 12 times per year? That could be (12,360) which is not visible instead we get (1,30) or once every 30 days. But a year has 365 days, so so we really mean (12,365) or once every 30.416 days? The difference between these two fractions is quite small $$ \frac{1}{30} - \frac{12}{365} = \frac{1}{2190}$$ Then this number 2190 place a big role in our corrections to the Calendar year. Our error is always on this scale. If we do this 10000 times, there may start to be noticeable problems.

Poincar recurrence theorem Pigeonhole Principle says our lives much have a very repetitive structure. I show up to work (5,7) days out of the week and have 12 nearby restaurants to choose from only about 3 I actually like. Instead of brining lunch, I ate at Subway 11 times this month, the chicken place 7 times in the month, and less requently ate out at the Thai place 2 times this month. About half the time I eat at subways, but less obviously it takes me about 2 days to get sick of their lack of variety. You will never see me eat Subways 3 days in a row.

In this way, the lack of variety forces our behavior into predictible Markov chains.

Open Question: Finding Empty Circles in a Collection of Points

The proposition says there are arbitrarily large patches of pairs of numbers, none of which are relatively prime, and they form a lattice. We can consturct intervals of numbers none of which are prime, such as $n! + k$ with $k = 0, 1, \dots, n$. This doesn't tell me how to construct pairs of intervals $(a,b) > 0$. In fact, the diagonal definitely won't work since $(a,a+1)=1$. Any kind of crazy factorial construction will produce very very large numbers. Instead, a systematic computer search may be in order. Algorithms for finding large empty circles in a random collection of points.

de Brujin's paper is confusing, and Beenker's paper allows me to get the confusing parts. Pentagrid patterns generate only some of the possible tilings.

for m in range(-N,N):
    for n in range(-N,N):

        z = inter(m + g[a], theta[a], n + g[b], theta[b])

        dt = 0.01

        pt = np.zeros((1,4))
        for t in np.arange(0,1+dt,dt):
            p = F(z + dt*np.exp(2j*np.pi*t))
            if not np.any(np.all((p == pt), axis=1)):
                pt = np.vstack((pt, [p]))
        rh = pt[1:]

        #print (m,n),
